<h3>
	Guide to displaying code blocks
</h3>

<h4>
	Syntax Highlighting
</h4>
<p>
	One easy way to have syntax highlighted code blocks on your site is to use <a href=https://code.google.com/p/google-code-prettify/>Google Code Prettify</a>. Repeating information from the <a href="http://google-code-prettify.googlecode.com/svn/trunk/README.html">README</a>, using Google Code Prettify on your site is as simple as adding the following code to the head of each page:

	<div align="center">
		<pre class="prettyprint lang-html inline rounded">
			<!-- uses google-code-prettify for syntax highlighting 
				 see https://code.google.com/p/google-code-prettify for more info -->
			<script type="text/javascript"
				    src="https://google-code-prettify.googlecode.com/svn/loader/run_prettify.js">
			</script>
		</pre>
	</div>
</p>

<p>
	See the Google code prettifier <a href=https://google-code-prettify.googlecode.com/svn/trunk/README.html>README</a> for supported languages and other relevant information.
</p>

<p>
	Also see the <a href="@pathto(documentation/nsm_tutorial)">nsm tutorial</a> for a better idea of how to nicely display code blocks. More to be added here at some point (probably no time soon). Alternatively, there are some examples below.
</p>

<h4>
	Example code blocks
</h4>

<div align="center">
	<pre class="prettyprint linenums lang-cpp rounded">
		<int> n;
		<vector> v;

		<pre>
			<int> n;
			<vector> v;

			for(int i=0; i < n; i++)
				cout << v[i] << endl;
		</pre>

		for(int i=0; i < n; i++)
			cout << v[i] << endl;
	</pre>
</div>

